  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"Rapid, concerted switching of the neural code in inferotemporal cortex\" by Yuelin Shi et al. has gained substantial early traction, as evidenced by 14 citations across various reputable venues such as Nature Reviews Neuroscience and PLoS Biology. This work demonstrates significant engagement within the neuroscience community, especially from key institutions including the California Institute of Technology and the University of California, Berkeley.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint \"Rapid, concerted switching of the neural code in inferotemporal cortex,\" authored by Yuelin Shi and colleagues, has notably influenced the neuroscience landscape since its release on bioRxiv. With a total of 14 citations, the work has been referenced in a variety of high-profile journals, notably including nine citations in bioRxiv and others in renowned publications such as Nature and PLoS Biology. This early impact is indicative of its significance and relevance in ongoing scholarly discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The citation patterns highlight a strong institutional backing for the research, with contributions from prestigious organizations like the California Institute of Technology and Howard Hughes Medical Institute. This affiliation not only underscores the credibility of the work but also enhances its visibility across multiple geographic regions, particularly the United States, Germany, and China. Such diverse institutional and geographical engagement emphasizes a broad interest in the findings of this research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the preprint is situated at the leading edge of scientific discourse in its field, as evidenced by its classification as a preprint among the citing work types. This positions the study as part of a dynamic and evolving conversation where findings are shared and debated within the academic community before formal publication. The decision to share early results demonstrates a commitment to open science, fostering prompt engagement and feedback from peers.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While there is currently no community discussion on platforms like Reddit or Bluesky, the absence of online mentions does not diminish the work's academic reception. Instead, the 15 proven downstream reuses of the data and materials illustrate that the findings are being actively integrated and built upon in subsequent research efforts. Overall, the work represents an essential contribution to the understanding of neural coding in the inferotemporal cortex, paving the way for further exploration and validation in future studies.</p>",
